:76},"'棕色'",[38,415,197],{"class":52},[38,417,418],{"class":76},"'小'",[38,420,171],{"class":52},[38,422,424,427,429,432,434,437],{"class":40,"line":423},25,[38,425,426],{"class":52},"console.",[38,428,154],{"class":48},[38,430,431],{"class":52},"(bibi.",[38,433,327],{"class":66},[38,435,436],{"class":52},"); ",[38,438,439],{"class":105},"\u002F\u002F Dog's constructor\n",[17,441,442,443,446,447,449,450,452,453,455,456,458],{},"At this point we know that ",[35,444,445],{},"bibi"," inherits from ",[35,448,291],{},"'s prototype, and ",[35,451,291],{}," in turn inherits from ",[35,454,125],{},"'s prototype. With this prototype chain concept, we can extend a whole bunch of things off ",[35,457,125],{}," — a cat prototype, a bird prototype, an insect prototype, and so on.",[17,460,461],{},[462,463],"img",{"alt":464,"src":465},"Prototype concept","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-02-27%2021.39.03.png",[17,467,468],{},"Earlier we learned that prototypes have this \"look upward\" behavior — when a property isn't found, the lookup keeps climbing. That behavior is exactly what we call the prototype chain.",[17,470,471,472,474,475,478,479,482,483,486,487,489,490,492,493,495],{},"For example, when ",[35,473,445],{}," (",[35,476,477],{},"var bibi = new Dog('bibi', '棕色', '小');",") looks upward, following ",[35,480,481],{},"__proto__"," lands us on ",[35,484,485],{},"Dog.prototype",". And how was ",[35,488,291],{},"'s prototype built? Mainly through ",[35,491,291],{},"'s constructor — and that constructor is what ",[35,494,327],{}," points back to. It's the bit below:",[28,497,499],{"className":30,"code":498,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"function Dog(name, color, size) {\n  Animal.call(this, '犬科')\n  this.name = name; \u002F\u002F dog's name\n  this.color = color; \u002F\u002F dog's color\n  this.size = size; \u002F\u002F dog's size\n}\n",[35,500,501,5